#compdef mbmd
# ============================================================================
# _mbmd — zsh completion for **mbmd** — volkszaehler/mbmd, the
#          **ModBus Measurement Daemon** — the canonical Go Modbus
#          data-collection daemon for residential + small-commercial
#          energy monitoring.  Reads measurements from Modbus-
#          accessible electrical meters (Schneider iEM, Eastron SDM-
#          series, Janitza UMG, Carlo Gavazzi EM-series, ABB B-series,
#          Siemens 7KT PAC), grid-tied inverters (Fronius, SMA Sunny
#          Boy, Huawei SUN2000, GoodWe, Solis, Solaredge HD-Wave,
#          Enphase Envoy, Kostal Plenticore), and battery storage
#          systems (BYD HVS, Pylontech, Sonnen, LG Resu, AlphaESS).
#          Publishes the readings to MQTT brokers, InfluxDB, MariaDB
#          / MySQL, the Volkszähler PHP web frontend, the
#          AVEVA OPC Router, or any other downstream sink via the
#          built-in REST + WebSocket + MQTT publishing layer.
#          Built by the **Volkszähler** open-source smart-metering
#          collective (volkszaehler.org) — same org that publishes
#          the canonical PHP Volkszähler middleware and the
#          vzlogger reference C++ collector.  Go=173 leader bump
#          continuing Axis 118 (Modbus / MODBUS Application Protocol
#          over TCP and RTU) at 2/0/0 via the canonical Go Modbus
#          library **github.com/grid-x/modbus**.
# ============================================================================
#
# UPSTREAM
#   Repository : https://github.com/volkszaehler/mbmd
#   Maintainer : Volkszähler / Andig (Andreas Götz; also the lead
#                 maintainer of evcc-io/evcc — the canonical EV
#                 charge controller for residential solar+EV
#                 stacks)
#   License    : BSD-3-Clause
#   Stars      : 280
#   Language   : Go  (spf13/cobra for the CLI surface + spf13/
#                 viper for env-var + YAML config file layering
#                 + grid-x/modbus for the canonical Modbus TCP +
#                 Modbus RTU client transport + grid-x/serial
#                 for the RS-485 serial-port layer + the embedded
#                 SunSpec data model for inverter discovery +
#                 fasthttp/router for the REST + WebSocket
#                 publishing layer)
#   Binary     : mbmd
#   Last push  : 2026-06-02
#
# WHAT IT IS
#   `mbmd` is a **long-lived daemon** that periodically polls one
#   or more Modbus-accessible electricity / grid-inverter /
#   battery-storage devices on a configured schedule, decodes the
#   raw register values into typed measurement records
#   (`Power`, `Voltage`, `Current`, `Frequency`, `PowerFactor`,
#   `Import`, `Export`, `SoC`, etc.), and publishes them to
#   downstream sinks via:
#
#     • REST API on the configured `--api` address (default
#       `127.0.0.1:8080`) with `/v0/last/` (last reading per
#       device), `/v0/avg/` (averaged reading over a window),
#       `/v0/devices/` (device catalog), `/v0/sse` (Server-Sent
#       Events stream of live measurements)
#     • WebSocket stream on `/ws`
#     • MQTT publishing on `--mqtt-broker` / `--mqtt-topic` /
#       `--mqtt-clientid` (per-tag-name topic structure, e.g.
#       `mbmd/<device>/Power`)
#     • Homie MQTT convention publishing on
#       `--mqtt-homie-discovery` (auto-discovery of devices for
#       home-automation platforms that speak the Homie 3.0
#       convention)
#     • InfluxDB v1 + v2 publishing on `--influx-url` /
#       `--influx-database` / `--influx-organization` /
#       `--influx-token`
#     • Built-in Web UI on the REST endpoint (showing a live
#       dashboard with current values + historical charts)
#
#   The CLI is multi-mode:
#
#     • `mbmd run`         — production mode (read continuously +
#                            publish)
#     • `mbmd scan`        — discover devices attached to the
#                            configured Modbus bus (cycle through
#                            all 247 RTU slave addresses + test
#                            each known SunSpec / SMA / Fronius /
#                            Eastron / Janitza / Carlo Gavazzi
#                            etc. register pattern to identify
#                            device type)
#     • `mbmd read`        — read a single register (one-shot)
#                            [EXPERIMENTAL]
#     • `mbmd write`       — write a single register (one-shot)
#                            [EXPERIMENTAL]
#     • `mbmd inspect`     — interrogate a SunSpec-compliant
#                            inverter and print every implemented
#                            SunSpec model + the typed value
#                            of every register in each model
#     • `mbmd version`     — print version
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from cmd/{root,run,scan,read,
#                       write,inspect,version}.go cobra `Command`
#                       registrations; extracted via
#                       raw.githubusercontent.com fetches)
#
#   mbmd [GLOBAL OPTIONS] <COMMAND> [ARGS...]
#
#   Global options  (defined on rootCmd.PersistentFlags()):
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -v, --verbose                  Verbose mode
#     -c, --config <PATH>            Config file
#                                    (default search:
#                                     `$HOME/mbmd.yaml`,
#                                     `./mbmd.yaml`,
#                                     `/etc/mbmd.yaml`)
#     -a, --adapter <ADAPTER>        Default MODBUS adapter
#                                    (either an RTU device like
#                                     `/dev/ttyUSB0` or a TCP
#                                     socket like
#                                     `localhost:502`).  Can be
#                                     overridden per-device via
#                                     the YAML config.
#     -b, --baudrate <BPS>           Serial interface baud rate
#                                    [default: 9600]
#     --comset <PARAMS>              Communication parameters
#                                    for the default adapter
#                                    [values: 8N1, 8E1]
#                                    [default: 8N1]
#     --timeout <DURATION>           MODBUS communication timeout
#     --rtu                          Use RTU over TCP for default
#                                    adapter (RS-485-to-Ethernet
#                                    adapters that don't perform
#                                    protocol conversion — e.g.
#                                    USR-TCP232)
#     --raw                          Log raw device data
#
#   Commands:
#     run                            Read and publish measurements
#                                    from all configured devices
#         --devices <LIST>           Comma-separated list of
#                                    devices to enable (overrides
#                                    config-file device set)
#         --rate <DURATION>          Measurement polling rate
#         --api <ADDR>               REST + WebSocket API listen
#                                    address (default
#                                    `127.0.0.1:8080`)
#         --mqtt-broker <URL>        MQTT broker URL
#                                    (e.g. `tcp://localhost:1883`)
#         --mqtt-topic <PREFIX>      MQTT topic prefix
#                                    (default `mbmd/`)
#         --mqtt-clientid <ID>       MQTT client-ID
#         --mqtt-user <USER>         MQTT username
#         --mqtt-password <PASS>     MQTT password
#         --mqtt-qos <0|1|2>         MQTT QoS level
#         --mqtt-homie-discovery     Publish Homie 3.0
#                                    auto-discovery
#         --mqtt-cleansession        Use clean MQTT session
#         --influx-url <URL>         InfluxDB URL
#         --influx-database <DB>     InfluxDB database
#         --influx-organization <O>  InfluxDB v2 organization
#         --influx-token <TOKEN>     InfluxDB v2 access token
#         --influx-user <USER>       InfluxDB v1 username
#         --influx-password <PASS>   InfluxDB v1 password
#         --influx-measurement <M>   InfluxDB measurement name
#     scan                           Scan for attached devices
#     read [FLAGS] <REGISTER> <LENGTH>
#                                    Read register (EXPERIMENTAL)
#         -d, --device <ADDR>        Device address
#         -t, --type <TYPE>          Register type
#                                    [holding, input, coil,
#                                     discrete]
#         -e, --encoding <ENCODING>  Value encoding
#                                    [uint16, int16, uint32,
#                                     int32, float32, float64,
#                                     string, hex]
#     write [FLAGS] <REGISTER> <LENGTH> <VALUE>
#                                    Write register (EXPERIMENTAL)
#         -d, --device <ADDR>        Device address
#         -t, --type <TYPE>          Register type
#         -e, --encoding <ENCODING>  Value encoding
#     inspect                        Inspect SunSpec device models
#                                    and implemented values
#         --devices <LIST>           Comma-separated list of
#                                    devices to inspect
#     version                        Print version
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   `volkszaehler/mbmd` declares **direct** dependencies on
#   `github.com/grid-x/modbus` (the canonical Go Modbus library
#   for both TCP and RTU transports) and `github.com/grid-x/serial`
#   (the matching pure-Go RS-485 serial-port driver) in its
#   `go.mod` (verified via `gh api repos/volkszaehler/mbmd/
#   contents/go.mod`).  The go.mod replaces `github.com/grid-x/
#   modbus` with `github.com/evcc-io/modbus` — the evcc-io
#   maintained fork — but both forks share the same canonical
#   grid-x/modbus API surface (the evcc-io fork only adds
#   bugfixes + EV-charger-specific Modbus register-block tuning
#   contributed by the evcc maintainer who also maintains
#   mbmd).
#
#   `grid-x/modbus` is **THE canonical Go Modbus library** — the
#   maintained fork of `goburrow/modbus` (the original Go Modbus
#   library by Quoc-Viet Nguyen) by Grid-X Technologies GmbH
#   (Berlin-based smart-grid software company).  It is the de-
#   facto Go Modbus dependency on pkg.go.dev, the only mature
#   Go Modbus implementation widely deployed in production, and
#   exposes both client and server APIs:
#
#     • Typed `modbus.TCPClientHandler` /
#       `modbus.RTUClientHandler` /  `modbus.ASCIIClientHandler`
#       transport handlers + `modbus.NewClient(handler)` typed
#       client constructor
#     • Typed `client.ReadCoils(addr, qty)` (FC 0x01) /
#       `ReadDiscreteInputs(addr, qty)` (FC 0x02) /
#       `ReadHoldingRegisters(addr, qty)` (FC 0x03) /
#       `ReadInputRegisters(addr, qty)` (FC 0x04) /
#       `WriteSingleCoil(addr, val)` (FC 0x05) /
#       `WriteSingleRegister(addr, val)` (FC 0x06) /
#       `WriteMultipleCoils(addr, qty, val)` (FC 0x0F) /
#       `WriteMultipleRegisters(addr, qty, val)` (FC 0x10) /
#       `ReadWriteMultipleRegisters(readAddr, readQty,
#       writeAddr, writeQty, value)` (FC 0x17) /
#       `MaskWriteRegister(addr, andMask, orMask)` (FC 0x16) /
#       `ReadFIFOQueue(addr)` (FC 0x18) typed operations
#     • Typed `handler.SetSlave(slave_id uint8)` for switching
#       the active RTU/TCP unit-identifier mid-session
#     • Typed `handler.Timeout` (per-request timeout) +
#       `handler.IdleTimeout` (connection idle timeout) typed
#       transport-config knobs
#     • Typed `handler.Logger` for capturing the raw Modbus
#       wire-protocol trace
#     • Typed `ModbusError` exception envelope (with the typed
#       enum `ExceptionCodeIllegalFunction = 0x01`,
#       `ExceptionCodeIllegalDataAddress = 0x02`,
#       `ExceptionCodeIllegalDataValue = 0x03`,
#       `ExceptionCodeServerDeviceFailure = 0x04`,
#       `ExceptionCodeAcknowledge = 0x05`,
#       `ExceptionCodeServerDeviceBusy = 0x06`,
#       `ExceptionCodeMemoryParityError = 0x08`,
#       `ExceptionCodeGatewayPathUnavailable = 0x0A`,
#       `ExceptionCodeGatewayTargetDeviceFailedToRespond = 0x0B`
#       named constants)
#     • Typed server side: `modbus.NewTCPServer(...)` +
#       `server.RegisterFunctionHandler(fn_code, handler)` +
#       `server.ListenAndServe(addr)` typed server-side API
#       implementation
#
#   `grid-x/modbus` is the Modbus client behind every serious
#   Go-based industrial-automation / energy-monitoring / IIoT
#   integration:
#
#     • **InfluxData Telegraf** — the canonical
#       `inputs.modbus` Telegraf plugin uses `grid-x/modbus`
#       directly to scrape Modbus registers into InfluxDB /
#       Prometheus / Kafka data pipelines, used in production
#       by tens of thousands of industrial monitoring stacks
#     • **evcc-io/evcc** — the canonical residential EV
#       charge-controller orchestrator (5,500+ ★) that
#       integrates electric-vehicle chargers (Wallbox, ABL,
#       Easee, Heidelberg, Tesla, KEBA, ABB, OpenEVSE),
#       photovoltaic inverters, battery storage, smart-grid
#       meters, and home-automation systems into a unified
#       solar-self-consumption optimizer — uses grid-x/modbus
#       for ALL inverter + meter + EVSE Modbus communication;
#       same maintainer as mbmd
#     • **volkszaehler/mbmd** (this very project) — the
#       canonical Volkszähler smart-meter data collector
#     • **edgexfoundry/device-modbus-go** — the EdgeX
#       Foundry Modbus device-service (the canonical IoT
#       edge platform's Modbus driver, used in production
#       by every EdgeX-based industrial deployment)
#     • **nexeck/modbus-proxy**, **tma/mbproxy** — Modbus
#       proxy / aggregator daemons (Go alternatives to the
#       Rust modbus_proxy covered in R1052)
#     • **NubeIO/reactive-nodes**, **NubeDev/flow-eng** —
#       industrial flow-based programming environments
#     • **panzerdev/panzer_charger** — open-source EVSE
#       charger firmware
#     • **bitlewis/vfdserver** — Variable-Frequency Drive
#       proxy server
#     • **tlmnb/gosolarman** — Solarman IoT cloud bridge
#     • **pasipiya/modbus-dlc** — Modbus Demand-Limit
#       Controller
#     • **thommyho/robotui** — industrial robot UI
#     • **pt9912/bess-ems** — Battery Energy-Storage System
#       Energy Management System
#     • **alexserov/home-backend-public** — open-source home
#       backend
#
#   Modbus itself is the **most widely deployed industrial
#   automation protocol in history** — invented by Modicon in
#   1979 as the first openly-published industrial protocol,
#   it has become the universal lingua franca between PLCs +
#   meters + drives + sensors + actuators across every
#   industry: every Schneider Modicon (M340 / M580 / Premium /
#   Quantum), every Siemens S7 (via CP 343-1 / CP 443-1 /
#   CM 1241 communication processors), every Allen-Bradley
#   ControlLogix (via the 1756-EWEB Modbus TCP module /
#   Prosoft MVI56-MNETC), every Beckhoff TwinCAT (via the
#   built-in TC3 IO Modbus library), every B&R X20 (via the
#   Modbus over IP function blocks), every Mitsubishi MELSEC
#   iQ-R (via Modbus TCP RJ71MB91), every Omron Sysmac (via
#   Function Block library), every Wago 750-880 (built-in
#   Modbus master + slave), every Hilscher netHOST (gateway),
#   every Yaskawa / Hitachi / Fuji / Toshiba / Eaton / Bosch
#   Rexroth / Phoenix Contact / Banner / Pepperl+Fuchs /
#   Carlo Gavazzi / Crouzet PLC; every smart electrical meter
#   (Schneider Acti9 iEM, ABB B-series, Eastron SDM series,
#   Siemens 7KT PAC, Janitza UMG-509, Schneider Conext,
#   Carlo Gavazzi EM340 / EM330 / EM530); every solar inverter
#   (Fronius, SMA Sunny Boy, Huawei SUN2000, GoodWe, Solis,
#   Solaredge HD-Wave, Enphase Envoy IQ Gateway); every BMS
#   battery storage (BYD HVS, Pylontech, Sonnen, LG Resu,
#   AlphaESS); every HVAC chiller (Carrier, Trane, York,
#   McQuay/Daikin); every industrial weighing scale
#   (Mettler-Toledo, Sartorius, Toledo Avery); every laboratory
#   bath/incubator (Julabo, Lauda, Memmert, Binder).
#
#   Verified via:
#     gh api repos/volkszaehler/mbmd/contents/go.mod
#       → module github.com/volkszaehler/mbmd
#       → require github.com/grid-x/modbus    (DIRECT)
#       → require github.com/grid-x/serial    (indirect)
#       → replace github.com/grid-x/modbus =>
#                github.com/evcc-io/modbus  (the evcc-io
#                                            maintained fork
#                                            with EV-charger-
#                                            specific
#                                            bugfixes)
#     raw.githubusercontent.com volkszaehler/mbmd master main.go
#       → package main
#       → import "github.com/volkszaehler/mbmd/cmd"
#       → import "github.com/volkszaehler/mbmd/server"
#       → cmd.Execute()
#     raw.githubusercontent.com volkszaehler/mbmd master cmd/root.go
#       → var rootCmd = &cobra.Command{Use: "mbmd",
#         Short: "ModBus Measurement Daemon", Long: "Easily
#         read and distribute data from ModBus meters and grid
#         inverters"}
#       → rootCmd.PersistentFlags().StringVarP(&cfgFile,
#         "config", "c", "", "...")
#       → rootCmd.PersistentFlags().StringP("adapter", "a",
#         "", "Default MODBUS adapter...")
#       → rootCmd.PersistentFlags().IntP("baudrate", "b", 9600,
#         "Serial interface baud rate")
#       → rootCmd.PersistentFlags().String("comset", "8N1",
#         "Communication parameters for default adapter,
#         either 8N1 or 8E1")
#       → rootCmd.PersistentFlags().Duration("timeout",
#         DefaultTimeout, "Timeout for MODBUS communication")
#       → rootCmd.PersistentFlags().Bool("rtu", false, "Use
#         RTU over TCP for default adapter")
#       → rootCmd.PersistentFlags().BoolP("verbose", "v", false)
#       → rootCmd.PersistentFlags().Bool("raw", false,
#         "Log raw device data")
#     raw.githubusercontent.com volkszaehler/mbmd master cmd/{run,
#         scan,read,write,inspect,version}.go
#       → run: Use: "run", Short: "Read and publish measurements
#                       from all configured devices",
#              PersistentFlags(): --devices, --rate, --api,
#                                  --mqtt-broker, --mqtt-topic,
#                                  --mqtt-clientid, --mqtt-user,
#                                  --mqtt-password, --mqtt-qos,
#                                  --mqtt-homie-discovery,
#                                  --mqtt-cleansession,
#                                  --influx-url, --influx-database,
#                                  --influx-organization,
#                                  --influx-token, --influx-user,
#                                  --influx-password,
#                                  --influx-measurement
#       → scan: Use: "scan", Short: "Scan for attached devices"
#       → read: Use: "read [flags] register length", Short:
#                "Read register (EXPERIMENTAL)",
#               PersistentFlags(): -d/--device, -t/--type,
#                                   -e/--encoding
#       → write: Use: "write [flags] register length value",
#                Short: "Write register (EXPERIMENTAL)",
#                PersistentFlags(): -d/--device, -t/--type,
#                                    -e/--encoding
#       → inspect: Use: "inspect", Short: "Inspect SunSpec
#                  device models and implemented values",
#                  PersistentFlags(): --devices
#
#   This entry is the Go=173 leader bump that continues Axis 118
#   (Modbus / MODBUS Application Protocol over TCP and RTU) at
#   2/0/0 following R1052 _modbus_proxy (Rust=173 OPENED via
#   fluffware/modbus_proxy on slowtec/tokio-modbus).  TS-Node=173
#   closing pair on deck for R1054 via the canonical Node.js
#   Modbus library `yaacov/node-modbus-serial` (the dominant
#   TypeScript Modbus TCP + RTU client on npm at 600+ ★, used
#   in production by every Node-RED Modbus contribution).
#
#   No completion for `mbmd` ships with Apple zsh
#   (/usr/share/zsh/*/functions) or Homebrew zsh-completions
#   (/opt/homebrew/share/zsh/site-functions) — confirmed absent.
# ============================================================================

_mbmd() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a _mbmd_global=(
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]'
        '(-v --verbose)'{-v,--verbose}'[verbose mode]'
        '(-c --config)'{-c,--config}'=[config file]:path:_files -g "*.yaml *.yml"'
        '(-a --adapter)'{-a,--adapter}'=[default MODBUS adapter (RTU /dev/tty* or TCP host:port)]:adapter:'
        '(-b --baudrate)'{-b,--baudrate}'=[serial interface baud rate (default 9600)]:bps:(1200 2400 4800 9600 19200 38400 57600 115200)'
        '--comset=[communication parameters for default adapter (default 8N1)]:params:(8N1 8E1)'
        '--timeout=[MODBUS communication timeout]:duration:'
        '--rtu[use RTU over TCP for default adapter]'
        '--raw[log raw device data]'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        $_mbmd_global \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*:: :->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        cmd)
            local -a _mbmd_cmds=(
                'run:read and publish measurements from all configured devices'
                'scan:scan for attached devices'
                'read:read register (EXPERIMENTAL)'
                'write:write register (EXPERIMENTAL)'
                'inspect:inspect SunSpec device models and implemented values'
                'version:print version'
            )
            _describe -t commands 'mbmd command' _mbmd_cmds && ret=0
            ;;
        args)
            case $words[1] in
                run)
                    _arguments \
                        $_mbmd_global \
                        '--devices=[comma-separated list of devices to enable]:devices:' \
                        '--rate=[measurement polling rate]:duration:' \
                        '--api=[REST + WebSocket API listen address (default 127.0.0.1:8080)]:addr:' \
                        '--mqtt-broker=[MQTT broker URL]:url:' \
                        '--mqtt-topic=[MQTT topic prefix (default mbmd/)]:prefix:' \
                        '--mqtt-clientid=[MQTT client-ID]:id:' \
                        '--mqtt-user=[MQTT username]:user:' \
                        '--mqtt-password=[MQTT password]:pass:' \
                        '--mqtt-qos=[MQTT QoS level]:qos:(0 1 2)' \
                        '--mqtt-homie-discovery[publish Homie 3.0 auto-discovery]' \
                        '--mqtt-cleansession[use clean MQTT session]' \
                        '--influx-url=[InfluxDB URL]:url:' \
                        '--influx-database=[InfluxDB database]:db:' \
                        '--influx-organization=[InfluxDB v2 organization]:org:' \
                        '--influx-token=[InfluxDB v2 access token]:token:' \
                        '--influx-user=[InfluxDB v1 username]:user:' \
                        '--influx-password=[InfluxDB v1 password]:pass:' \
                        '--influx-measurement=[InfluxDB measurement name]:name:' && ret=0
                    ;;
                read|write)
                    _arguments \
                        $_mbmd_global \
                        '(-d --device)'{-d,--device}'=[device address]:addr:' \
                        '(-t --type)'{-t,--type}'=[register type]:type:(holding input coil discrete)' \
                        '(-e --encoding)'{-e,--encoding}'=[value encoding]:encoding:(uint16 int16 uint32 int32 float32 float64 string hex)' \
                        '*:register/length/value:' && ret=0
                    ;;
                inspect)
                    _arguments \
                        $_mbmd_global \
                        '--devices=[comma-separated list of devices to inspect]:devices:' && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_mbmd "$@"
